nus Torvalds &lt;&gt;</td></tr><tr><td class="lp">Subject</td><td class="rp" itemprop="name">Re: Security question: "Text file busy" overwriting executables but not shared libraries?</td></tr></table></td><td><div class="shariff" data-services="[&quot;reddit&quot;]" data-theme="grey" data-lang="en" data-backend-url="//shariff.lkml.org/index.php"></div></td></tr></table><pre itemprop="articleBody"><br />On Sat, 13 Oct 2001, Jamie Lokier wrote:<br />&gt;<br />&gt; In fact it was proposed here on this list years ago, and I think you<br />&gt; argued against it (TLB flush costs).  The costs and kernel<br />&gt; infrastructure have changed and maybe the idea could be revisited now.<br /><br />It's still not entirely unlikely that doing VM mappings is simply more<br />expensive than just doing a memcpy. The TLB invalidate is only part of the<br />issue - you also have the page table walk, the VM lock, and the fact that<br />PAGE_COPY itself ends up being overhead.<br /><br />Which is why the PAGE_COPY kind of read() optimization is _probably_ only<br />worth it if the user asks for it directly (or automatically only for large<br />reads together with single-threaded applications).<br /><br />The explicit flag is probably a good idea also because of usage patterns<br />(PAGE_COPY is a slowdown _if_ the file is actually written to or even<br />mapped shared).<br /><br />		Linus<br /><br />-<br />To unsubscribe from this list: send the line "unsubscribe linux-kernel" in<br />the body of a message to majordomo&#64;vger.kernel.org<br />More majordomo info at  <a href="http://vger.kernel.org/majordomo-info.html">http://vger.kernel.org/majordomo-info.html</a><br />Please read the FAQ at  <a href="http://www.tux.org/lkml/">http://www.tux.org/lkml/</a><br /><br /></pre><div align="center"><div class="shariff" data-services="[&quot;reddit&quot;]" data-theme="grey" data-lang="en" data-backend-url="//shariff.lkml.org/index.php"></div></div></td><td width="32" rowspan="2" class="c" va